In the conflict the Principal os Hart Hall, then Fellow os Exeter, a scholar ol St. Alban’s Hah, and ¹another of Staple Hall were slain, besides many others who were wounded. Several Merton men were engaged in the light, of whom Mr. John Foster, Principal os St. Alban's Hall was the chief ; also Mr. Philip Dense and Mr. John Wingar, who with their gowns flung aside were present in the crowd' Riots at Oxlord were so frequent at this time that there were thoughts os taking away the privileges ol the Univer- sity3 ‘and without doubt it would so have come to pass, had not Warham, Archbishop ol Canterbury, laboured seasonably with importunate requests to the contrary!

In 1580, ‘since several decrees had been made for the orderly keeping of the act, Dr. Mattheus, Dean oi Christ Church, who was this year Vice·Chancellor‚ resolved to see them severely observed, and soreseeing some rudeness that was like to be done by the juniors on Act Monday‚ kept the door leading to the scafiolds (built theatre-wise at the east end ol St. Mary's Church) in his own person. And among the divers academicians that endeavoured to enter, and were by him repelled, was Dr. Harris, Principal of Brasenose college, who, though a Head and consequently en- titled to a place there, was with scorn (the Vice- Chancellor being probably in a passion) thrust down.'
